    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="804"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d804">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/19354</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Berle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-28">January 28,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary</hi>: I telephoned the President today in
                    respect of the St. Lawrence Waterway. While on the telephone I told him that we
                    had news that Thailand had declared war;<note n="6" xml:id="d804fn6">January 25;
                        for official notification, see telegram No. 350, February 2, from the Chargé
                        in Switzerland, <ref target="#pg_915">p. 915</ref>.</note> but that you had
                    approved the policy of ignoring the matter. The President said he cordially
                    agreed.</p>
                <p>He then said that he thought it would be a good idea if you were to write a note
                    to the Chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee of the Senate and the
                    Chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the House,<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d804fn7">Letters of February 7 to Senator Tom Connally and
                        Representative Sol Bloom not printed.</note> stating quite briefly that the
                    Department had been informed that declarations of war on the United States had
                    been made by Hungary, Rumania, Bulgaria<note n="8" xml:id="d804fn8">Hungarian
                        and Bulgarian declarations made on December 13, 1941; Rumanian declaration
                        on December 12, 1941.</note> and Thailand; and that no action appeared to be
                    required.</p>
                <p>I said I would pass the suggestion along. The President’s idea was that this
                    would merely complete the record and treat the declarations with the contempt
                    they deserved.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>A. A. B[<hi rend="smallcaps">erle</hi>], <hi rend="smallcaps">Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
